export default "# Using Multiple SSH Keys for GitHub (Personal + Work)\n\nThis guide explains how to configure multiple SSH keys and use them with different GitHub accounts on the same machine.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Verify Existing SSH Keys\n\nCheck your SSH directory:\n\n```bash\nls -al ~/.ssh\n```\n\nExample:\n\n```\nid_ed25519_personal\nid_ed25519_personal.pub\nid_ed25519_work\nid_ed25519_work.pub\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Add SSH Key to GitHub\n\n### Personal Account\n\nCopy your public key:\n\n```bash\ncat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_personal.pub\n```\n\nThen:\n\n1. Go to GitHub → Settings → **SSH and GPG keys**\n2. Click **New SSH key**\n3. Add:\n\n   * **Title**: `personal-mac`\n   * **Key**: (paste copied key)\n\n---\n\n## Step 3: Configure SSH (`~/.ssh/config`)\n\nCreate or edit the SSH config file:\n\n```bash\nnano ~/.ssh/config\n```\n\nAdd the following:\n\n```ssh\n# Personal GitHub\nHost github-personal\n    HostName github.com\n    User git\n    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_personal\n\n# Work GitHub\nHost github-work\n    HostName github.com\n    User git\n    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_work\n```\n\nSave and exit.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4: Set Remote URLs\n\n### For Personal Repositories\n\n```bash\ngit remote set-url origin git@github-personal:pradhanhitesh/<repo-name>.git\n```\n\n### For Work Repositories\n\n```bash\ngit remote set-url origin git@github-work:<work-username>/<repo-name>.git\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 5: Test SSH Connection\n\n### Personal\n\n```bash\nssh -T git@github-personal\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```\nHi pradhanhitesh! You've successfully authenticated...\n```\n\n### Work\n\n```bash\nssh -T git@github-work\n```\n\n---\n\n## Important Notes\n\n* Do **NOT** use:\n\n  ```bash\n  git@github.com:<username>/<repo>.git\n  ```\n\n  This uses the default SSH key and may cause conflicts.\n\n* Always use:\n\n  * `github-personal`\n  * `github-work`\n\n---\n\n## Optional: Set Git Identity per Repo\n\nInside a repository:\n\n```bash\ngit config user.name \"Hitesh Pradhan\"\ngit config user.email \"your-personal-email@example.com\"\n```\n\nFor global config:\n\n```bash\ngit config --global user.name \"Hitesh Pradhan\"\ngit config --global user.email \"your-email@example.com\"\n```\n\n---\n";